<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-09-06T01:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-09-06T01:00:00-05:00" n="873" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d873">
                    <note rend="inline" type="source">793.003/9–644: Telegram</note>
                    <head>
                        <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Gauss</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                        </hi>
                    </head>
                    <opener>
                        <dateline rendition="#right">
                            <placeName>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Chungking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-09-06T13:00:00+07:00">September 6,
                                1944—1 p.m.</date>
                            <lb/> [Received September 6—12:18 p.m.]</dateline>
                    </opener>
                    <p>1513. I saw Foreign Minister yesterday, reurtel 1163, September 1. He stated
                        that as areas concerned are still in Jap hands no action has been taken but
                        he sees no reason why provisions of articles II and III of treaty cannot be
                        implemented satisfactorily when Diplomatic Quarter and Settlements are taken
                        over. He inquired what particularly Department had in mind in making its
                        inquiry.</p>
                    <closer>
                        <signed>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Gauss</hi>
                        </signed>
                    </closer>
                </div>
                </body></text></TEI>